Invistico Airlines Project: 2nd case¶

Objectives
2nd case
The airline is interested in predicting whether a future customer would be satisfied with all of their services given previous customer feedback about their total flight experiences. The airline would like the construction and evaluation of a model that can accomplish this goal. They are also interested in knowing which features of the total flight experience are most important to customer satisfaction.

Deliverables
The data is sample size of survey responses from 129,880 customers. It includes data points such as satisfaction, class, flight distance, and inflight entertainment, among others. It is an in-house product.

Models
(Since this project is a portfolio addition, the models are predetermined. Since this is a labelled data set, all models qualify as supervised.)

2nd case: Tree-based classification machine learning model (2nd notebook)
In the second case, the airline is interested in predicting whether a future customer would be satisfied with their flight experience given previous customer feedback. They are also interested in knowing which features of their flight experience are most predictive of that satisfaction. Decision trees are classification models that can handle all of the types of variables this data set contains (categorical, discrete, and continuous). They make predictions for a target variable based on multiple variables (features). Because decision trees return a weighted map of possible outcomes to any series of related choices, the airline can use these findings to allot their available resources.

For this second case 3 tree based models are trained, tuned, evaluated, and compared for the most predictive power. The most predictive will be tested on the unseen test data.\

    1. Simple decision tree: can handle collinearity and has no assumptions about data distribution. This works well for this data set, since its variables have highly uneven distributions and scales.
    2. Random Forest: these models leverage randomness by combining the results of many models to help make more reliable final predictions. These predictions have less bias, and lower variance than other standalone models. They are also very scalable (thus can handle outliers easily, which is also a factor in this data set) and less susceptible to overfitting.
    3. Gradient Boosting (XGBoost): these models have a high accuracy rate, work well with missing data (which this data set has), are scalable, and can provide a weighted feature importance chart. However, as they are considered black-boxes, their steps cannot be seen (the trees cannot be produced).

The goal will be to utilize the best decision tree model to predict whether or not a customer will be satisfied(y) with their flight experience based on multiple variables in the data set(Xs) and discover which variables are most predictive of that outcome.

PART III: 2nd CASE¶

Build 3 tree-based classification machine learning models¶

    1. Simple decision tree: can handle collinearity and has no assumptions about data distribution. This works well for this data set, since its variables have highly uneven distributions and scales.
    2. Random Forest: these models leverage randomness by combining the results of many models to help make more reliable final predictions. These predictions have less bias, and lower variance than other standalone models. They are also very scalable (thus can handle outliers easily, which is also a factor in this data set) and less susceptible to overfitting.
    3. Gradient Boosting (XGBoost): these models have a high accuracy rate, work well with missing data (which this data set has), are scalable, and can provide a weighted feature importance chart. However, as they are considered black-boxes, their steps cannot be seen (the trees cannot be produced).

1. Build baseline decision tree¶

  • Train a baseline model to get a sense of how predictive the data is
  • Get data points(scores) that can be referenced later

Split the data into:

  • features and target variable
  • training data(75%) and test data(25%)
  • no need to stratify, because data set is balanced
  • set a random seed so work can be reproduced (0)

# Create confusion matrix to visualize how accurate classifier is at predicting the labels
# Calculate the values for each quadrant in the confusion matrix
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, DT_pred, labels = decision_tree.classes_) # decision_tree.classes_ (classifications)

# Visualize confusion matrix
disp = ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix = cm, display_labels=['dissatisfied(0)', 'satisfied(1)']) # display_labels = clf.classes_

disp.plot();

Legend

  • True label (y_test): actual labels of the holdout sample
  • Predicted label (DT_pred): predicted labels (satisfied/dissatisfied [decision_tree.classes_]) on the holdout test sample

Since this is a binomial logistic regression, there are only two labels, 0 and 1

  • 0 = the person was labeled as dissatisfied for that observation
  • 1 = a person was labeled as satisfied for that observation

Translation

  • True negatives(UL): # of people that were dissatisfied(0) that the model accurately predicted as dissatisfied(0) = 13607

  • True positives(LR): # of people that were satisfied(1) that the model accurately predicted were satisfied(1) = 16661

  • False positives(UR)/ Type I Errors: # of people that were dissatisfied(0) that the model inaccurately predicted were satisfied(1) = 1035

  • False negatives(LL)/Type II Errors: # of people that were satisfied(1) that the model inaccurately predicted were dissatisfied(0) = 1069

Immediately seen from the model is a very high proportion of true positives and true negatives (where the matrix accurately predicted that the customer would be satisfied or dissatisfied, respectively) to false positives and false negatives.

There is also a proportional relationship between false positives and false negatives (where the matrix inaccurately predicted that the customer would be satisfied or dissatisfied, respectively. There are very few false positives and false negatives.

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

dissatisfied       0.93      0.93      0.93     14642
   satisfied       0.94      0.94      0.94     17730

    accuracy                           0.94     32372
   macro avg       0.93      0.93      0.93     32372
weighted avg       0.94      0.94      0.94     32372

Precision: measures the % of customers that are actually satisfied out of all the customers that have been predicted to be satisfied (# true positives(16661) / (# true positives(16661) + # false positives(1035))

The good
This model has a precision score of 0.94, thus it is excellent at precisely predicting whether an airline customer will be satisfied (true positives), based on the feature variables. In an effort to be precise, the model also attempts to reduce the occurrences of incorrectly classifying people as satisfied when they are dissatisfied (false positives/Type I errors).

The bad
In its goal to be precise (not classify people as satisfied when they are dissatisfied), the algorithm can become more selective. A higher rate of precision may mean that more samples are classified as dissatisfied, when then are satisfied (false-negative/Type II errors). Thus, satisfied customers can be missed, especially with such a high precision score.

The conclusion:
Because the airline is interested in learning if a new customer would be satisfied based on their current inflight entertainment, an 94% satisfaction rate is excellent. This is particularly true if the algorithm has even missed satisfied people.

Recall: measures the % of satisfied customers that the classifier correctly identified as satisfied out of all satisfied observations in the test set (21208). (# true positives(16661) / (# true positives(16661) + # false negatives(1069))

The good
This model has a precision score of ~0.94, thus it is excellent at correctly identifying whether the airline passenger will be satisfied, based on the feature variables, out of all customers who were tagged as satisfied (y_test = 32372 [17730 + 14642]). The model is also less likely miss people who are satisfied (to incorrectly classify people as dissatisfied who are satisfied (false-negative/Type II errors)).

The bad
However, because the model is more sensitive to finding satisfied people, it can be prone to incorrectly categorizing people as satisfied (false-positives/Type-I error) when they are dissatisfied.

The conclusion
With the exceptionally high score of ~94% the airline may not want to put too much stock in this metric – since some people would have been dissatisfied with it and possibly would not have been classified as such. The score of ~0.94 (or 1035 missed people), may not weigh heavily.

Accuracy is the percentage of data points that were correctly classified out of all total predictions (# true positives(16661) + # true negatives(13607) / # total predictions(38847)). The model achieved an accuracy score of ~0.94 which is excellent.

The bad
Accuracy can be misleading if the data set is unbalanced. The algorithm could be poor at balancing false positive and false negatives because it does not account for the distribution of classes (satisfied/dissatisfied). It could be excellent at predicting one class (e.g., the majority) and being terrible at predicting the other (e.g., the minority) and return a very good accuracy score.

The conclusion
Since this class was mostly balanced (17730 (1)/ 14642 (0)), an accuracy of ~0.94 likely reflects a well balanced result.

F1 Score (the harmonic mean) balances precision (minimizing false positives or Type I errors) and recall (minimizing false negatives or Type II errors) performance, providing a single value for evaluation.

The conclusion
The combined F1 score of 0.94 is excellent. It means that the model is highly effective at minimizing both type of errors. However, because decision trees are prone to overfitting, this result is a bit suspect.

Plot baseline decision tree¶

Produce a visual representation of the tree to pinpoint where the splits in the data are occurring

In [105]:
# Plot tree
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plot_tree(decision_tree, max_depth=3, fontsize=12, feature_names=X.columns,
          class_names={0:'dissatisfied', 1:'satisfied'}, filled=True); # filled=True gives colors 
plt.show()

Will a future customer would be satisfied with their services given previous customer feedback?

The 1st line in each node(box) gives: the feature and split point that the model identified as being most predictive
In this case, it asks if the Inflight entertainment score was <= to 3.5?

The 2nd line gives the gini impurity rating, which can range from 0 to 0.5

  • 0 = there is no impurity (all samples in the leaf) are of a single class)
  • 0.5 = the classes are all equally represented in that node In this case Inflight entertainment is represented very evenly

The 3rd line gives the number of samples in the node ([43963 (dissatisfied), 53152 (satisfied)] = 97115) This tells us that 43963 customers in this node were dissatisfied (y=0) and 53152 customers were satisfied (y=1) (with the entertainment).

The 4th line gives the majority class of the samples in each node: satisfied

Conclusion
This tree informs that the most predictive feature for classifying if a person was satisfied is Inflight entertainment.
Following down the tree, the next splits are at Seat Comfort and Ease of online booking, demonstrating that they are the second most predictive features.
Near purity does not happen until a depth of 3.
Because Seat Comfort and Ease of online booking are features 2nd in predictability and very striated, it would be good to perform further analytics on them.

Calculating and plotting feature importances aggregated the results seen in the plotted tree. 'Inflight entertainment' is the most important feature with 'Seat comfort' being rather important. 'Ease of Online booking' is not as predictive as originally suggestive. It is slightly more predictive than the remaining variables, which are all fairly equally in productivity.
No one seems interested in Inflight WiFi service.
Perhaps surprisingly, for this model, delays of either sort did not weigh heavily in predictability.

Create metrics results table function¶

1st: create new df

  • results = pd.DataFrame(columns=[]) 2nd: define function using make_results(model_name, model_object)
  • get all the results from the CV and put them in a df
  • isolate the row of the df with the max(mean f1 score)
  • extract accuracy, precision, recall, and f1 score
  • create table
In [37]:
# Create a metrics results table function
results = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model', 'Precision', 'Recall', 'Accuracy', 'F1']) # These are the cols

def make_results(model_name, model_object):  # model_name = name, model_object = clf/rf/gbx
    cv_results = pd.DataFrame(model_object.cv_results_)
    best_estimator_results = cv_results.iloc[cv_results['mean_test_f1'].idxmax(), :] # idxmax() returns a series with the index of the max value for each col
    f1 = best_estimator_results.mean_test_f1
    recall = best_estimator_results.mean_test_recall
    precision = best_estimator_results.mean_test_precision
    accuracy = best_estimator_results.mean_test_accuracy

# Create table of results
    table = pd.DataFrame({'Model': [model_name],
                          'Precision': [precision],
                          'Recall': [recall],
                          'Accuracy': [accuracy],
                          'F1': [f1]
                         })
    return table

Results of Best Decision Model: Random Forest¶

The objective of this random forest model is to predict whether a future customer would be satisfied with all of Invistico airlines services given previous customer feedback about their total flight experiences and to uncover which features of a customer’s airline experience were most predictive of their satisfaction. Unlike the previously built logistic regression model (PART I), which used only the variable Inflight entertainment as the independent predictive variable to predicate whether the inflight entertainment experiences of previous customers can indicate future customer satisfaction, this random forest model maximizes predictability by using all features (independent Xs) present in the data set. The model performs supremely. Using the dependent binary variable Satisfaction the model predicts with a near 100% accuracy score which customers will be satisfied (and dissatisfied) based on all features.

On the whole, previous customers were fairly split in their satisfaction with their overall experience of the airline. ~55% of customers were satisfied and ~45% were dissatisfied. Out of the 32372 people in the test data, 17730 were satisfied. Of these, the model missed only 94 satisfied people, thereby achieving a ~99% recall score. The model also scored ~100% on precision (with a f1 of ~100%), thus it has an equally high ability to identify satisfied or unsatisfied customers and an equally low chance of falsely identifying satisfied or unsatisfied customers (Type I and Type II errors). Further demonstrating this model's efficacy, it achieved an AUC score of ~100%, which suggests a near perfect performance over all possible classification thresholds in distinguishing between positive and negative classes.

Because the model scored so highly in all metrics, it is difficult to suggest further optimization. Optimizing either precision or recall scores, would likely result in either more false positives, where it would attempt to reduce the occurrences of incorrectly classifying people as satisfied when they are dissatisfied (Type I errors) or more false-negatives where more people would be classified as dissatisfied, when then are satisfied (Type II errors).

The most predictive feature in customer satisfaction as ascertained by the model was inflight entertainment, with seat comfort and ease of online booking also being somewhat predictive. Inflight wifi service was not the least predictive variable as it had been in non-winning models; however, perhaps surprisingly, delays either in arrival or departure had the lowest predictive effect. The extreme success of the model indicates that the airline should focus attention on their inflight entertainment service, either leaving it as it is or continuing to improve it based on customer feedback. As the model scored an ~100% on accuracy, this is far better predictor than the ~55% satisfaction rating for the overall dataset.
